ve an account of the organization of the historicity that yields the emergence of something like the African American, at once with its own internal dimensions and yet also as an originary articulation of forces and possibilities that have world historical implications. Chandler refigures Du Bois’s thought as a vital theoretical resource for rethinking our concepts of differences among humans and, so too, our understanding of modern historicity itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsyTo 1964. 0aAfrican Americans-Civil rights-19th century. 0aAfrican Americans-Social conditions-To 1964. 0aDu Bois, W. E. B.-(William Edward Burghardt),-1868-1963-Political and social views. 0aUnited States-Race relations. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023029?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023029/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles